Deleting, Copying, Moving, and Renaming files

Deleting files
Copying files
Moving files
Renaming files
Compress files
Creating archives

rm file    -> Removing file
rm -r dir  -> Remove the directory and its contents recursively
rm -f file -> Force removal and never prompt for confirmation
$ ls s*
$ rm s*

ls -d .*
rm .*


Copy Files
cp source_file destination_file -> Copy source_file to destination_file

cp src_file [src_fileN ...] dest_dir
source_file to destination_directory

cp -i -> Run in interactive mode
cp -r source_directory destination copy src_directory recursively to destination
Example cp -r dir dir2 dir3 recurselvy copies the two file dir and dir2 to directory dir3

mv -> Move or rename files and directories
mv -> Source destination
mv -> -i source destination


sort Options
Sorts Alphabetical 
-k F Sort by key. F is the field number
-r sort in reverse order
-u sort sort unique it igonres dupliate records


Creating a Collection of Files
tar [-] c|x|t f tarfile [pattern]
Creat,extract or list contents of a tar archive using pattern, if supplied
tar options
C Create a tar archive
X Extract files from the archive
t Display the table of content (list)
V Be verbose i.e show files that its etracting explicity
Z Use compression
f file use this file or specify the file going to use

Example 
$ tar cf tps.tar 
$ tar tf tps.tar
$ tar zcf tps.tgz


Disk Usage
du Estimate the file usage
du -k Display size in kb
du -h Display size in human readable format

examples
$ du -k fname
$ gzip fname
$ ls fn*
$ gunzip fname.qz


Summary

rm delete files
cp copy files
mv move files and directories
gzip to compress
tar to create archives






 








